hire, England","Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Abergavenny, Herefordshire, England":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Marbury in Great Budworth, or, perhaps, from Marbury cum Quoisley (both in Cheshire). Both placenames derive from Old English <i>mere</i> ‘pool, lake’ + <i>burh</i> ‘fortress’ (dative <i>byrig</i>), ‘stronghold by the lake’.","variant of <b>Marbrow</b>, itself a variant of <b>Marlborough</b>, a habitational name from Marlborough (Wiltshire), which probably derives from an Old English personal name <i>Mǣrla</i> + Old English <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Marbry","meanings":["English: variant of   Marbury  ."]},{"name":"Marberry","meanings":["Altered form of English   Marbury  ."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":1,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":14,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":68,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Joyce Marbury was born in 1314, in Cheshire, England, her father, Sir Robert Marbury, was 24 and her mother, Bromwich, was 26. She had at least 3 sons and 3 daughters with Sir John Scudamore."},"et":{"1314–":"1314–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1305–1385":"1305–1385","1335–1409":"1335–1409","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","Abt 1348":"umbes 1348","1385":"1385","Abt 1335":"umbes 1335","Abt 1346":"umbes 1346","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1